## How It Works

### Asset Hierarchy

Tero.Ops models the physical structure of fishing operations natively. Assets support unlimited parent-child nesting:

```
Fleet (Company)
└── Vessel (Worksite: VESSEL)
    └── Main Engine (Asset)
        └── Fuel Pump (Asset)
            └── Pump Seal (Asset)
```

Each asset node carries its own maintenance history, linked spare parts from inventory, meter associations, and a scannable QR code. What sets Tero.Ops apart is that this hierarchy is not a generic equipment tree adapted from a facility management tool — it models maritime asset structures out of the box.

### Maintenance Scheduling

Tero.Ops supports four job occurrence types:

```
Occurrence Types:
  ONE_OFF          → single scheduled event
  TIME_BASED       → recurring on a calendar interval
  METER_BASED      → triggered when meter reading crosses a threshold
  WHICHEVER_FIRST  → earliest of TIME_BASED or METER_BASED
```

The key difference is the `WHICHEVER_FIRST` trigger. Unlike MaintainX, which supports calendar and meter scheduling as separate job types without a combined earliest-trigger mode, Tero.Ops resolves both conditions in a single job definition — a pattern specific to marine engine maintenance where both hours and calendar intervals apply simultaneously.

### Offline-First Mobile Operations

Tero.Ops operates as an offline-first Progressive Web App (PWA) using a full Workbox 6.6.x service worker suite — precaching, background sync, broadcast update, and range requests. Native iOS and Android builds are packaged via Capacitor 6.1.2. Field technicians access cached asset records, log job records, and record meter readings with zero connectivity. Data syncs automatically when the vessel returns to port.

Unlike UpKeep, which is a cloud-first CMMS with an offline mode added as a secondary capability, Tero.Ops is designed from the ground up to operate with zero connectivity — local-first data architecture is not an afterthought.

